comments.content: PHB-2, along with PHB-1, forms the mitochondrial inner membrane Prohibitin complex which is implicated in assembly of components of the respiratory chain.

Activation of the UPRmt correlates with enhanced binding of DVE-1 to the promoters of mitochondrial chaperone genes. DVE-1 was found to bind the hsp-6 and hsp-60 gene promoters by Chromatin ImmunoPrecipitation (ChIP).

ubl-5 RNAi results in diminished expression of an hsp-6::GFP reporter and endogenous hsp-6. dve-1 RNAi also disrupts induction of endogenous hsp-6 expression induced by spg-7 RNAi, as determined by QRT-PCR.

RNAi knockdown of dve-1 prevents expression of a Phsp-60::GFP reporter transgene in response to the zc32 allele at 25 degrees Celsius, spg-7 RNAi, or exposure to Ethidium Bromide (all known to induce UPRmt and, hence, hsp-60 expression). dve-1 RNAi also disrupts induction of endogenous hsp-60 expression induced by spg-7 RNAi, as determined by QRT-PCR. ubl-5 RNAi results in diminished expression of an hsp-60::GFP reporter and endogenous hsp-60.

Unfolded protein stress in the mitochondria correlates with complex formation between a homeodomain-consisting transcription factor DVE-1 and the small ubiquitin-like protein UBL-5, both of which are encoded by genes required for signaling the UPRmt.

haf-1, a gene encoding a mitochondria-localized ATP-binding cassestte protein, is required for signaling within the mitochondrial unfolded protein response (UPTmt) and for coping with misfolded protein stress. Peptide efflux from isolated mitochondria was ATP dependent and required HAF-1 and the protease ClpP.
gsp-1 encodes a protein phosphatase homologous to the yeast phosphatase required for eIF2-alpha dephosphorylation.
During UPRmt activation, ATFS-1::GFP accumulated in nuclei
Activation of the mitochondrial unfolded protein response (UPRmt) correlates temporally and spatially with nuclear redistribution of DVE-1.

HSP-60 is the C. elegans ortholog of the mitochondrial chaperone protein HSP60. hsp-60 RNAi induces expression of the Phsp-6::GFP and Phsp-60::GFP transgenes, supporting the model of a negative feedback loop of mitochondrial chaperone expression.

HSP-6 is the C. elegans ortholog of the mitochondrial chaperone protein HSP70. hsp-6 RNAi induces expression of the Phsp-6::GFP and Phsp-60::GFP transgenes, supporting the model of a negative feedback loop of mitochondrial chaperone expression.
gsp-1 encodes a protein phosphatase homologous to the yeast phosphatase required for eIF2-alpha dephosphorylation. gsp-1 RNAi results in increased phosphorylation of eIF2-alpha (Y37E3.10)

Ethidium bromide preferentially impairs replication and transcription of the mitochondrial genome, reducing synthesis of mitochondrially encoded polypeptides. Exposing worms to ethidium bromide results in specific upregulation of expression of the hsp-6 and hsp-60 genes, encoding mitochondrial chaperone proteins, as determined by Northern blot of endogenous hsp-6 as well as increased expression of the Phsp-6::GFP and Phsp-60::GFP transgenes

Translational fusion ATFS-1::GFP was nearly undetectable under normal conditions, although the atfs-1 was sufficient to drive GFP expression under normal conditions, suggesting constitutive degradation of ATFS-1
A knockout mutation in haf-1 (allele ok705) results in an accumulation of ATFS-1 in mitochondria and less ATFS-1 in the cytosol

SPG-7 is a mitochondrial membrane metalloprotease; knockdown of spg-7 by RNAi results in accumulation of mitochondrially localized GFP and specific upregulation of expression of nuclear-encoded, mitochondrial chaperone proteins HSP-6 and HSP-60 as determined by Phsp-6::GFP and Phsp-60::GFP transgene reporters (both by fluorescence microscopy and western blot) and by northern blot of endogenous hsp-6 mRNA

Although individual knockout of the D2030.2 gene (encoding a ClpX-like mitochondrial protease) with the tm2183 deletion allele did not affect expression of an Phsp-60::GFP reporter transgene, simulataneous knockdown of both ClpX-like proteases, D2030.2 and K07A3.3, attenuated expression of the Phsp-60::GFP transgene in response to the zc32 mutation.
Mitochondrial stress promotes accumulation of GFP-tagged UBL-5 in nuclei of transgenic worms.
gcn-2 encodes an eIF2-alpha kinase. Knockout mutations in gcn-2 result in reduced phosphorylation of eIF2-alpha
RNAi knockdown of phb-2 results in increased expression of the nuclear-encoded mitchondrial chaperone gene hsp-60, as indicated by expression of the Phsp-60::GFP reporter transgene

The mitochondrial unfolded protein response (UPRmt) is attenuated in animals with reduced activity of clpp-1, which encodes a mitochondrial matrix protease homologous to bacterial ClpP. clpp-1 RNAi results in disruption of the UBL-5/DVE-1 complex and interferes with expression of the ubl-5 and dve-1 genes. Paraquat induces expression of the nuclear-encoded mitochondrial chaperone gene hsp-60, as indicated by expression of the Phsp-60::GFP reporter transgene
dnj-10 expression was found to be down-regulated in an atfs-1 knockout mutant
atfs-1 (ZC376.7) RNAi abolishes expression of an Phsp-60::GFP reporter transgene in response to the zc32 mutation or RNAi of the hsp-6 or spg-7 genes.

Unlike wild-type worms, atfs-1(tm4525) (deletion mutation of atfs-1) animals were unable to induce hsp-60pr::gfp when raised on spg-7(RNAi), a mitochondrial protease required for ETC quality control and mitochondrial ribosome biogenesis. atfs-1(tm4525) knockout mutants failed to induce expression of endogenous hsp-60 in response to spg-7 RNAi, as determined by RT-PCR.

comments.content: "Mitochondria are required for numerous essential metabolic processes including the regulation of apoptosis; therefore, proper maintenance of the mitochondrial proteome is crucial. The protein-folding environment in mitochondria is challenged by organelle architecture, the presence of reactive oxygen species and the difficulties associated with assembly of the electron transport chain, which consists of components encoded by both the mitochondrial and the nuclear genomes. Mitochondria have dedicated molecular chaperones and proteases that promote proper protein folding, complex assembly and quality control. Work in cultured mammalian cells and Caenorhabditis elegans has yielded clues to the mechanisms linking perturbations in the protein-folding environment in the mitochondrial matrix to the expression of nuclear genes encoding mitochondrial proteins. Here, we review the current knowledge of this mitochondrial unfolded protein response (UPRmt), compare it with the better understood UPR of the endoplasmic reticulum and highlight its potential impact on development and disease." (Haynes and Ron 2010)
